SIMPLE: falcon
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Falcon
<hw>Fal"con</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>faucon</ets>, <ets>faucoun</ets>, OF. <ets>faucon</ets>,
<ets>falcon</ets>, <?/. <ets>faucon</ets>, fr. LL. <ets>falco</ets>,
perh. from L. <ets>falx, falcis</ets>, a sickle or scythe, and named
from its curving talons. Cf. <er>Falchion</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>One of a family
(<fam>Falconid⟦ae⟧</fam>) of raptorial birds, characterized by a short,
hooked beak, strong claws, and powerful flight.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>Any species of the genus <gen>Falco</gen>, distinguished by having
a toothlike lobe on the upper mandible; especially, one of this genus
trained to the pursuit of other birds, or game.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the language of falconry, the female peregrine (<spn>Falco
peregrinus</spn>) is exclusively called the <qex>falcon</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Yarrell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Gun.)</fld> <def>An ancient form of
cannon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Chanting falcon</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See
under <er>Chanting</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Falconer</ent>⟦br⟧
